powerline-buffer-id: Avoid double-expanding %-escapes (#192)

Formerly, powerline-buffer-id would call format-mode-line multiple
times on the mode-line-buffer-identification, which was wrong in the
case of buffer names that include percent signs.

Use powerline-display-{buffer-size,hud} where appropriate (#163)

The powerline-display-buffer-size and powerline-display-hud variables
currently only have effect on the default theme. This patch makes them
apply to the center and center-evil themes as well.

Add encoding segment (#132)

This commit adds an option to view the encoding of a file in
Powerline by taking the functionality from TheBB's Spaceline.
By adding something like (powerline-encoding face2 'r) to
your custom powerline theme either "unix", "dos", "mac" or
"utf-8" will display in your Powerline with the selected
face.

Make Powerline Faces Customisable Without Touching the Mode-Line (#146)

* Use White Font Colour With Dark Backgrounds

The default powerline setup uses realtively dark background colours. The
default mode-line setup on the other hand uses black text on relatively
light greys. Hence, the result when installing powerline over a vanilla
Emacs mode line is black text on very dark grey, i.e. close to indiscernible.
Hence, changing the text colour on dark backgrounds to white.

* Make Powerline Faces Customisable Without Touching the Mode-Line Face

I introdcued a third font face as powerline-active0 and powerline-inactive0.
Apart from the "center evil" theme (which didn't work for me so I didn't
touch it), all themes have been updated to use this third font face
instead of the mode-line font face (i.e. to configure the left- and
rightmost parts of the mode line). The new faces default to the mode-line
and mode-line-inactive faces respectively, so the default behaviour of
the change is backwards compatible, and existing configurations will
remain unaffected by upgrading to this.

Background: I wanted the left and right parts (where left part holds the
buffer name) to be in a bright colour. To achieve this, I had to set the
mode-line face to have the desired background colour. Undesired side
effect is that "auxiliary" buffers like speedbar, RefTeX toc, etc. become
more visually calling by adopting the bright mode-line background colour.
By not modifying the mode-line face, those auxiliary buffers retain the
default look and feel, whereas buffers in which I am actually editing use
the powerline look and feel and stick out nicely.

* Small Oversight In Default Theme

Missed out on the space between the buffer id and the first separator.

Fix image colors on MacOS (#141)

Fixes #54.

Adds a custom option 'powerline-image-apple-rgb', which should be set
to 't' to enable the workaround. When the option is set, powerline's
XPM images are generated using equivalent Apple RGB colors, instead of
the regular sRGB colors.

This is not needed on the Emacs-mac port, or when Apple RGB colors are
used by setting 'ns-use-srgb-colorspace' to nil.
